        "content": "<p><code>rw [@AddSemigroup.add_assoc]</code> should just be <code>rw [add_assoc]</code> and <code>exact CommMonoid.mul_comm a b</code> should be <code>exact mul_comm a b</code> (these are more idiomatic).</p>",
        "id": 499089772,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1739304477
    },
    {
        "content": "<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">CommRing</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">DivisionRing</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">IsField</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>This is not provable. Both <code>CommRing</code> and <code>DivisionRing</code> are data, so they put e.g. two different additions and multiplications on <code>R</code>.</p>",
        "id": 499090518,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1739304726
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks! My mental model here was clearly off, and I realize I have some reading to do. (If you have any recommendations for a resource that thoroughly explains the difference between data-carrying and non-data-carrying structures, I'd really appreciate it—I've struggled with this concept before.)</p>\n<p>When I read <code>(R : Type) [CommRing R] [DivisionRing R] : IsField R</code>I naively think that assuming a type <code>R</code> that satisfies the contracts of both a <code>CommRing</code> and a <code>DivisionRing</code>, we claim that is can be show that <code>R</code> fulfills the contract of a <code>Field</code>.</p>\n<p>I now understand where my reasoning goes wrong: Lean treats these as two separate structures, meaning the two additions and two multiplications (of <code>CommRing </code> and <code>DivisionRing</code> respectively) may not coincide.</p>\n<p>To force them to coincide, the correct approach is to bundle the structures into a single, unified structure?</p>\n<p>My naive attempt might be:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">class</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">CommDivisionRing</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kn\">extends</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">CommRing</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">DivisionRing</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">CommDivisionRing</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">IsField</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Would this avoid the problem?</p>\n<p>What would be a better, more idiomatic way to do it?</p>\n<p>Essentially, I want to demonstrate that a commutative ring that also functions as a division ring is, in fact, a field. (I guess one alternative approach could be to show the source code definitions of <code>Field</code>, <code>CommRing</code>, and <code>DivisionRing</code> side by side. However, I believe it would be more approachable to illustrate this using <code>example</code> blocks instead.)</p>",
        "id": 499096223,
        "sender_full_name": "Isak Colboubrani",
        "timestamp": 1739307170
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think part of the confusion is that sometimes my flawed mental model of this ends up giving the right result (unfortunately). </p>\n<p>Consider these two examples:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">CommRing</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">IsDomain</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Finite</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">IsField</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">exact</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Finite</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">isField_of_domain</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">CommRing</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">DivisionRing</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">IsField</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>The first example is correct, but the second one is not? Is this because <code>DivisionRing</code> is a data-carrying structure while <code>IsDomain</code> and <code>Finite</code> are not?</p>\n<p>Is there a naming convention that indicates when a structure is non-data-carrying—I would guess at least everything prefixed <code>Is</code> is not data-carrying? Or more generally, how do I know is a structure is data-carrying or not?</p>",
        "id": 499099953,
        "sender_full_name": "Isak Colboubrani",
        "timestamp": 1739308664
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In your <code>CommDivisionRing</code> case, you can use</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">CommDivisionRing</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">IsField</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">@</span><span class=\"n\">Field</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">toIsField</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"bp\">__</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">inferInstance</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">CommDivisionRing</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">)}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>though this is just an obscure way of saying: <code>CommDivisionRing</code> and <code>Field</code> have the same properties.</p>",
        "id": 499100139,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1739308739
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"321459\">@Damiano Testa</span> <code>hint</code> suggests <code>exact IsArtinianRing.isField_of_isDomain R</code>.</p>\n<p>That was not what I expected! :)</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">class</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">CommDivisionRing</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kn\">extends</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">CommRing</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">DivisionRing</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">CommDivisionRing</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">IsField</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">exact</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">IsArtinianRing</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">isField_of_isDomain</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Is the introduction of a new <code>class CommDivisionRing</code> a sane way to do this (to demonstrate with an <code>example</code> that a commutative ring that also functions as a division ring is, in fact, a field), or is there an alternative method that would be more idiomatic?</p>",
        "id": 499101350,
        "sender_full_name": "Isak Colboubrani",
        "timestamp": 1739309257
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you are trying to show what implications there are among the various typeclasses, I would say that this is a good way to show how things work.</p>",
        "id": 499102893,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1739309940
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you were building a mathematical library, I would suggest thinking <em>really</em> hard about whether there is any advantage to introducing a new typeclass that is \"the same\" as an existing one.</p>",
        "id": 499103049,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1739310006
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Wrt the proof that I suggested and the one found by <code>hint</code>, I think that there is pedagogical value in both.</p>",
        "id": 499103155,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1739310052
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The one that I suggested basically tells you that the fields of <code>Field</code> are all contained among the fields of <code>CommDivisionRing</code>.</p>",
        "id": 499103247,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1739310093
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The one found by <code>hint</code> leverages the typeclass system to find a proof and actually has some mathematical content, since the implication (Artinian + domain =&gt; Field) is not just moving around axioms (inasmuch as some tautologies are less obvious than others).</p>",
        "id": 499103564,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1739310235
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"321459\">@Damiano Testa</span> Yes, to clarify: these examples are solely for demonstration purposes. I consider them analogous to the summaries a student might jot down during a lecture, but written in Lean using Mathlib instead of on paper, to illustrate how concepts might look when formalized.</p>",
        "id": 499104256,
        "sender_full_name": "Isak Colboubrani",
        "timestamp": 1739310504
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Don't we have something like <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Commute#doc\">docs#Commute</a> ?</p>\n<p>You can tell if something is data-carrying by hovering over it and seeing if it's a <code>Type</code> or a <code>Prop</code>. If I had my way you'd also be able to tell by seeing if the name begins with <code>Is</code> or not, but this is less reliable right now.</p>",
        "id": 499146444,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1739334526
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh hmm, <code>Commute</code> is not a typeclass. I would just go for <code>DivisionRing</code> and then add the hypothesis that <code>\\forall a b, a * b = b * a</code>.</p>",
        "id": 499146733,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1739334697
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Isn't that a field?</p>",
        "id": 499176542,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruben Van de Velde",
        "timestamp": 1739349985
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh, that's what you're showing</p>",
        "id": 499176596,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruben Van de Velde",
        "timestamp": 1739350005
    }
